Yes — this should become its own Ansible-owned network role/playbook.

Right now, your uploaded `deploy_server.py` still has the network mutation in Python: `deploy_interface()` discovers the active NetworkManager connection, checks current IPv4 settings, then runs `nmcli connection modify ...` and `nmcli connection up ...`; `run_deploy_server()` still calls `deploy_interface(...)` before running the PXE/controller playbooks.  

The clean fix is:

```text
aerolitctl configure server
  writes saved network intent

aerolitctl deploy server
  refreshes generated Ansible vars
  runs configure_network.yml
  runs pxe_server.yml
  runs ansible_controller.yml

configure_network role
  makes the actual nmcli changes
```

I would name it:

```text
playbook: configure_network.yml
role:     configure_network
vars:     configure_network_*
```

